supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil. audiam cum eis

p.note: Top right corner: National Library modern ex libris. Lower part of page in brown ink: 247.
Top of page in black ink by a medieval hand: F 2o 10us (shelfmark from the Vadstena library).
Entire page in brown ink by 18th/19th(?) century hand: table of content.
Middle of page in black ink by a medieval hand: scattered words and letters (probbaly pen-trial).

binding.p: Contemporary binding from Vadstena Monastery. Brown leather over wooden boards. 4 double bands and endbands. 2 hook-clasps with long clasps and short leather straps. , in brown ink: CC; in black ink: 131; stamped in gold: A 32; brown ink on torn label: 32.

Binding probably by Niels Bookbinder, active in Vadstena at the end of the 15th century; see Collijn (1903)
. Several examples of stamps used by Niels are found in Sten G. Lindberg’s archive, Kungliga Biblioteket, Band 10:4 Niels–band och andra gnidebilder, Acc. 2005/28.

decoNote.p: Blind-tooling. : Double frame filled with stamps of fleur-de-lis and roses. Panel blind stamped with large lozenges filled with vegetative shapes. : Multi-line frame. Diamond pattern panel filled with multiple stamps of fleur-de-lis and roses. , , and : Blind-tooling also found on the edges of the cover.

binding.condition: Covers torn and cracked in places. Endbands and one of the raised bands exposed.

provenance.p: The manuscript belonged to the library in Vadstena. In the manuscript was transferred to the National Archives by Johannes Bureus, see Gödel (1916) Appendix 2 and 3 .

Later the manuscript was transferred to the Antiquities Archive and is listed in its inventories and catalogues. There are 3 unique signa on the , two of which have been identified. The older, 131, is found in the inventory from 1720 (U 90:2, f. 12v) and the current signum, ‘A 32’, was first established in Helin’s catalogue from the 1720s (U 91:2:2).
Also mentioned in the following catalogues and inventories: U 90:1, MSS in folio, nr. 145; U 90:4, p. 58, nr 131; U 91:1, nr. I 131.

acquisition.p: From the Antiquities Archive to the National Library in .

msItem.title: Revelations, Book 8

supportDesc.foliation: Running titles in red ink (occasionally also in green).
supportDesc.condition: Holes in the parchment throughout the manuscript, but no loss of text. Some of the holes are circled with red ink, e.g. on . Text legible. Several leaves have been cut out (see collation), but this has been done before the text was written. There is no loss of text.

p.note: Marginal additions and corrections by a contemporary hand in the form of letters, single words, short phrases, and manicules.

decoDesc.p: Main text in black ink, capitals touched in red, rubrics in red. : final rubric in green speech scroll.

decoNote.p: , , penwork initial I over 8-9 lines in green with red flourishing. : penwork inital M in red over 6 lines. : inhabited initial C in red and green over 10 lines. Counter space filled with a ram and hound drawn in black ink, as well as vegetative ornamnets in red and green ink. Inital placed in red frame with flourishing and vegetative ornaments in green and black. : knotwork inital O over 10 lines, outlined in black ink, then filled with vegetative ornamnets in red and green. Inital placed in black and red frame with flourishing and vegtative ornaments in green and black. : vinestem inital V over 7 lines in black ink. This inital has not been filled in with colours. : plain initials over 3-4 lines in green with red flourishing or red with green flourishing. : plain initials in black with red flourishing over 2-3 lines. : plain Initials over 2-4 lined in green or red.
